threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered ransomware. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: PE32 executable (GUI) Intel 80386, for MS Windows

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The analyzed binary is a sophisticated Ransomware variant that implements advanced persistence, privilege escalation, and lateral movement capabilities. Key malicious behaviors include: 1) Privilege Escalation: sub_402f69 identifies the shell window (Explorer.exe) to duplicate its token via DuplicateTokenEx and CreateProcessWithTokenW, allowing the malware to execute under a user's session context. 2) Defense Evasion: sub_4032fa uses Toolhelp32 snapshots to enumerate and terminate processes, a common tactic for disabling security software. 3) Lateral Movement: sub_401b7d recursively enumerates network resources and shares using WNetOpenEnumW/WNetEnumResourceW to identify remote files for encryption. 4) Data Encryption: sub_404d46 and sub_405193 utilize the Windows CryptoAPI (CryptImportKey, CryptEncrypt) to perform file encryption on local drives (discovered via GetLogicalDrives in sub_40104e) and network shares. 5) Persistence: sub_40129d copies the binary to a new location and modifies Registry Run keys (RegSetValueExW) to ensure execution on system startup.
